UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1857
1 3. Deceptive actions;
2 (4) "Department" means the Department of Professional Licensing in the Public
3 Protection Cabinet;
4 (5) "Licensed professional":
5 (a) Means an individual who holds a valid license or certificate issued by any
6 agency of this Commonwealth to provide therapy or psychotherapy services,
7 including:
8 1. A licensed psychologist licensed under the provisions of KRS Chapter
9 319;
10 2. A licensed clinical social worker licensed under the provisions of KRS
11 335.100;
12 3. A certified social worker licensed under the provisions of KRS
13 335.080;
14 4. A professional counselor credentialed under the provisions of KRS
15 335.500 to 335.599;
16 5. A marriage and family therapist licensed under the provisions of KRS
17 335.500 to 335.599;
18 6. A licensed alcohol and drug counselor licensed under the provisions
19 of KRS 309.080 to 309.089 authorized to provide therapy or
20 psychotherapy services;
21 7. An art therapist certified under KRS 309.130;
22 8. An advanced practice registered nurse licensed under the provisions of
23 KRS Chapter 314 engaged in providing mental health services; and
24 9. Any other professional authorized by this Commonwealth through a
25 license or certificate to provide therapy or psychotherapy services; and
26 (b) Does not include a physician;
27 (6) "Peer support" means services provided by individuals with lived experience of
Page 2 of 6
XXXX 1/20/2026 4:36 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1857
1 mental health conditions or recovery from substance use that are intended to
2 offer encouragement, understanding, and guidance without clinical intervention;
3 (7) "Permitted use of artificial intelligence" means the use of artificial intelligence
4 tools or systems by a licensed professional to assist in providing administrative
5 support or supplementary support in therapy or psychotherapy services where the
6 licensed professional maintains full responsibility for all interactions, outputs,
7 and data use associated with the system and satisfies the requirements of Section
8 2 of this Act;
9 (8) "Relevant board" means the applicable state board that licenses, certifies,
10 regulates, or oversees the specific type of licensed professional;
11 (9) "Religious counseling" means counseling provided by clergy members, pastoral
12 counselors, or other religious leaders acting within the scope of their religious
13 duties if the services are explicitly faith-based and are not represented as clinical
14 mental health services or therapy or psychotherapy services;
15 (10) "Supplementary support" includes but is not limited to the:
16 (a) Preparing and maintaining of client records, including therapy notes;
17 (b) Analyzing of anonymized data to track client progress or identify trends,
18 subject to review by a licensed professional; and
19 (c) Identifying and organizing of external resources or referrals for client use;
20 (11) "Therapeutic communication":
21 (a) Means any verbal, nonverbal, or written interaction conducted in a clinical
22 or professional setting that is intended to diagnose, treat, or address an
23 individual's mental, emotional, or behavioral health concern; and
24 (b) Includes but is not limited to:
25 1. Direct interactions with clients for the purpose of understanding or
26 reflecting their thoughts, emotions, or experiences;
27 2. Providing guidance, therapeutic strategies, or interventions designed
Page 3 of 6
XXXX 1/20/2026 4:36 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1857
1 to achieve mental health outcomes;
2 3. Offering emotional support, reassurance, or empathy in response to
3 psychological or emotional distress;
4 4. Collaborating with clients to develop or modify therapeutic goals or
5 treatment plans; and
6 5. Offering behavioral feedback intended to promote psychological
7 growth or address mental health conditions; and
8 (12) "Therapy or psychotherapy services":
9 (a) Means services provided to diagnose, treat, or improve an individual's
10 mental health or behavioral health; and
11 (b) Does not include religious counseling or peer support.
12 SECTION 2. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 367 IS CREATED TO
13 READ AS FOLLOWS:
14 (1) A licensed professional:
15 (a) Shall not use artificial intelligence to assist in providing supplementary
16 support in therapy or psychotherapy services where the client's therapeutic
17 session is recorded or transcribed unless:
18 1. The patient or the patient's legally authorized representative is
19 informed in writing of the following:
20 a. That artificial intelligence will be used; and
21 b. The specific purpose of the artificial intelligence tool or system
22 that will be used; and
23 2. The patient or the patient's legally authorized representative provides
24 consent to the use of artificial intelligence;
25 (b) May use artificial intelligence only to the extent it is a permitted use of
26 artificial intelligence and the use meets the requirements of this section;
27 (c) Shall not allow artificial intelligence to:
Page 4 of 6
XXXX 1/20/2026 4:36 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1857
1 1. Make independent therapeutic decisions;
2 2. Directly interact with clients in any form of therapeutic
3 communication;
4 3. Generate therapeutic recommendations or treatment plans without
5 review and approval by the licensed professional; or
6 4. Detect emotions or mental state; and
7 (2) An individual, corporation, or entity shall not provide, advertise, or otherwise
8 offer therapy or psychotherapy services, including through the use of internet-
9 based artificial intelligence, to the public in this Commonwealth unless the
10 therapy or psychotherapy services are performed by an individual who is a
11 licensed professional.
12 (3) All records kept by a licensed professional and all communications between an
13 individual seeking therapy or psychotherapy services and a licensed professional
14 shall be confidential and shall not be disclosed except as required by KRS
15 210.235.
16 SECTION 3. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 367 IS CREATED TO
17 READ AS FOLLOWS:
18 (1) Any individual, corporation, or entity found to be in violation of Sections 1 to 3 of
19 this Act shall pay a civil penalty to the department in an amount not to exceed ten
20 thousand dollars ($10,000) per violation, as determined by the department, with
21 penalties assessed based on the degree of harm and the circumstances of the
22 violation.
23 (2) A civil penalty shall be:
24 (a) Assessed by the department after a hearing is held by the relevant board;
25 and
26 (b) Paid within sixty (60) days after the date of an order by the relevant board
27 imposing the civil penalty.
Page 5 of 6
XXXX 1/20/2026 4:36 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1857
1 (3) The relevant board shall have authority to investigate any actual, alleged, or
2 suspected violation of Sections 1 to 3 of this Act.
3 (4) Sections 1 to 3 of this Act do not apply to religious counseling, peer support, or
4 self-help materials and educational resources that are available to the public and
5 do not purport to offer therapy or psychotherapy services.
6 Section 4. Whereas the General Assembly seeks to protect vulnerable
7 Kentuckians from harm caused by artificial intelligence, an emergency is declared to
8 exist, and this Act takes effect upon its passage and approval by the Governor or upon its
9 otherwise becoming a law.
